post_text:
Hermantown is proud to join the MSHSL's #BeTheLightMN movement.

Every Monday, in April and May, at 8:20 pm (20:20) the baseball field lights will be turned on for 20 minutes, 20 seconds to honor our students, staff, and community in this time of distance learning due to COVID-19.

Our buildings may be closed, but let these lights remind you that Hermantown is shining brightly. Lighting up our community during these challenging times can bring hope to everyone driving by. We ask that you enjoy the lights from afar and keep our community safe. Sometime soon we will gather under the lights again, fill our school buildings with learning and laughter, and turn ALL the lights back on.

For now, know you are missed and you are not alone! Hawks always fly together! #BeTheLightMN #hawksflytogether

The Hermantown Counseling Department wants to let you know we are thinking about all of you and your students. Our hope is that in these times of uncertainty and new challenges, you are taking care of yourselves and finding ways to connect to those you love.

We know this situation in general, including the implementation of distance learning, may be hard for some while others may be very ready to navigate online learning. Wherever youâ€™r e at, weâ€™re in this together. We are here to support and help you and your family through this time.

Your students are very special to us and we miss seeing them each day. Although we may not be there in person, we can connect through email, phone calls, or video. If there is something you or your student needs from our Counseling Department, please reach out to the building counselor.

All the best,
Hermantown Counseling Department

post_text:
Starting on Monday, March 30th, please be sure to have your child or children login to their school Google account and check Google Classrooms each day. Assignments will not be given everyday, but students should login each day. Our teachers have been instructed to not overwhelm students with work to begin with, so the distance learning activities will likely start out minimal and build over time.

If your child is sick, you may call in to the office as in the past, but attendance for distance learning will be monitored by checking to see if your child has logged into their Google account and/or completed and submitted work to their teachers. If we see that a student is not logging in to their school account, we will reach out to parents to check. For those who do not have Internet access, we will be creating a list of students, putting together paper copies of work, and having the paper copies delivered with a schedule to be determined.

This process is new to everyone...teachers, students, and parents...so if you have questions, please reach out to teachers or the office.

post_text:
Parents / Guardians of High School Students,

Here are two brief announcements regarding our school closure from March 18-27. First, no high school students will be allowed in the high school building. There may have been a miscommunication from one or more staff members, but to be clear, no high school students will be let in the building during the March 18-27 timeframe. This may be extended based on recommendations from the state government. If you have a question or need to drop-off or pick-up an item, you may contact the main office, but no visitors will be allowed past the main entrance doors.

Second, the spring Parent-Teacher Conferences scheduled for Thursday, April 2nd are postponed. Due to the school closure, the 3rd Quarter grading period has been extended to Friday, April 3rd. Rescheduling the spring Parent-Teacher Conferences will depend upon the date the school reopens.

Please check your email and/or campus inbox for updates as they come available.

John Muenich
High School Principal

post_text:
We will have normal school hours Monday and Tuesday. Beginning Wednesday, March 18 and through our upcoming Spring Break, school will be closed in order for staff to prepare for an extended period of closure.

Those that volunteer in the buildings are asked to stay home this week.

Please be aware that this situation is changing constantly and is being closely monitored by our entire educational community. There will a couple of surveys coming out tomorrow that will help in our planning, and your timely response to them will be greatly appreciated.

If you don't feel comfortable sending your child to school Monday and Tuesday, we understand and will count them as excused absences.

These are uncharted waters for all of us, but they still need to be navigated - and we're doing our best.

Respectfully,
Kerry Juntunen, Superintendent

post_text:
Evacuation of Middle School and High School

There is the smell of gas in the high school's boiler room. As a precaution, the Middle School and High School are being evacuated to the Hermantown Ice Arena. Students who drive themselves have been asked to leave immediately. Buses will be loading students on the Ugstad Road side of the Arena. if you're picking up your child from the Arena, you will enter the administration parking lot on the Arrowhead Road side. The elementary school will stay in session through the end of the day.

post_text:
Early Dismissal Today

There was a gas leak on a rooftop air handling unit. The gas was shut off to the unit earlier this morning and we've been assured that there is no imminent danger. While the situation is being cared for by our maintenance staff and other professionals, it is in the interest of safety to close the High School and Middle School at noon today. Buses will be loading at 12:10 PM. The elementary school will stay in session

post_text:
Do you have a child interested in Hockey or Basketball Cheerleading?

If your student is interested:

We are holding a tryout/interest meeting on Tuesday, September 24th from 4:30-5:30. My current cheerleaders will be having practice beforehand and interested parties are welcome to come join us right after school.

On this day we will cover basic motions, the school song, a cheer and some jumps. Please come wearing tennis shoes, athletic clothes and ready to learn.

We will be meeting on the Track if the weather permits if not we will meet by the amphitheater outside the digital commons.

If you have a student interested in trying out and can not make it September 24th, other arrangements can be made. Please contact Ms. Rahn at mrahn@isd700.org

Period 2 Final Exam - 8:00 a.m. - 9:15 a.m.

Hermantown Middle School Student Council is holding a toy and winter clothing drive for kids in need this holiday season.

Do you have toys and winter clothes you donâ€™t need anymore? Donate them!

Bring in new or gently used outdoor winter clothing and toys for families in need!

Collection will take place at the Hermantown Middle School Commons - December 11th - December 20th

Each grade will have a collection box for donated items. The grade level with the most items will win a grade level party!
